1 Introduction

In this notebook, we summarize the doublet detection results obtained after running Scrublet. In particular, we run Scrublet for each accessible matrix derived from individual 10X Chip Channels, as recommended in their notes on best practices.

2 Histograms

We start plotting the doublet score histograms for observed epigenome and simulated doublets. We should observe a bimodal distribution in the simulated doublets allowing us to set an accurate threshold. Although Scrublet was designed to detect doublets in scRNA-seq, SnapATAC authors1 Fang, Rongxin, et al.SnapATAC: a comprehensive analysis package for single cell ATAC-seq." bioRxiv (2020) have suggested that this tool can also be used to find doublets in scATAC-seq datasets as well.

path_to_hist <- paste0("tmp/histograms/scrublet_doublet_prediction_histograms-",gem_id, ".png")

Figure 1: Histogram with the automatic threshold determined by Scrublet

3 UMAPs

As described in the Scrublet best practices: - Visualize the doublet predictions in a 2-D embedding (e.g., UMAP or t-SNE). Predicted doublets should mostly co-localize (possibly in multiple clusters). If they do not, you may need to adjust the doublet score threshold, or change the pre-processing parameters to better resolve the cell states present in your data.

path_to_umap <- paste0("tmp/umaps/scrublet_doublet_prediction_umaps-",gem_id, ".png")

Figure 2: Umap with the automatic threshold determined by Scrublet
